@Node "WBAddAppIcon" "RxWB Functions - WBAddAppIcon"

  @{b}WBAddAppIcon@{ub} - creates an appicon.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    appIconID = WBAddAppIcon(name,icon)
    <name>,[icon],[stem]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Adds an appicon on the workbench screen. An appicon is a
    standard AmigaOS appicon.

    @{i}name@{ui} is the name of the appicon.

    @{i}icon@{ui} is the name of a info file, without the .info suffix.
    If @{i}icon@{ui} is not given or the icon can't be found, the system
    tools default icon is used.

    @{i}stem@{ui} is an ARexx stem name; in it you may set the field:
    - SupportsOpen
    - SupportsCopy
    - SupportsRename
    - SupportsInformation
    - SupportsSnapshot
    - SupportsUnSnapshot
    - SupportsLeaveOut
    - SupportsPutAway
    - SupportsDelete
    - SupportsFormatDisk
    - SupportsEmptyTrash
    - PropagatePosition
    - NotifySelectState

    The above have sense only under AmigaOS 3.5.

    The appicon is freed at the exit of the macro if it wasn't
    yet.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    name - the name of the appicon
    icon - the icon file to use


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    appIconID - the appicon ID


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAppIconSignal" LINK "WBAppIconSignal"} @{"WBFreeAppIcon" LINK "WBFreeAppIcon"} @{"WBHandleAppIcon" LINK "WBHandleAppIcon"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBAppIconSignal" "RxWB Functions - WBAppIconSignal"

  @{b}WBAppIconSignal@{ub} - returns an appicon signal.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    signal = WBAppIconSignal(appIconID)
    <appIconID/N>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    @{i}appIconID@{ui} is the ID of an appicon created with WBAddAppIcon().
    The functions returns the signal to wait for appicon events.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    appIconID - an appicon ID


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - the signal of the appicon


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAddAppIcon" LINK "WBAddAppIcon"} @{"WBFreeAppIcon" LINK "WBFreeAppIcon"} @{"WBHandleAppIcon" LINK "WBHandleAppIcon"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBFreeAppIcon" "RxWB Functions - WBFreeAppIcon"

  @{b}WBFreeAppIcon@{ub} - deletes an appicon.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    call WBFreeAppIcon(appIconID)
    <appIconID/N>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Deletes an appicon created with WBAddAppIcon().

    appIconID is the appicon ID returned by WBAddAppIcon().


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    appIconID - an appicon D


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    none


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAddAppIcon" LINK "WBAddAppIcon"} @{"WBAppIconSignal" LINK "WBAppIconSignal"} @{"WBHandleAppIcon" LINK "WBHandleAppIcon"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBHandleAppIcon" "RxWB Functions - WBHandleAppIcon"

  @{b}WBHandleAppIcon@{ub} - handles an appicon.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    numMsg = WBHandleAppIcon(appIconID,handle)
    <appIconID>,<handle/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Handles an appicon.

    @{i}appIconID@{ui} is the appicon ID returned by WBAddAppIcon().

    The following fields of @{i}handle@{ui} can be set:

    - WAIT
      Wait for messages from the appicon, default 1

    - CTRLC
      Wait for a ctrl-c as well, default 0

    - SIGNALS
      Wait for this signals too, default 0

    The functions returns the number of the messages pending and sets
    the fields:

    - handle.i.CLASS that can be:
      . DOUBLECLICK
        The user doubleclicked the icon

      . DROP
        Icons were dropped over this appicon
        i = 0,...,n n = numMsg-1

      . DOUBLECLICK

      . COPY

      . RENAME

      . INFORMATION

      . SNAPSHOT

      . UNSNAPSHOT

      . LEAVEOUT

      . PUTAWAY

      . DELETE

      . FORMATDISK

      . EMPTYTRASH

      . SELECTED

      . UNSELECTED

   If the class is DROP there are set the fields:
   - .i.DROPNUM
     The number of icons dropped

   - .i.NAME.j
     The name of the j-th icon

   - .i.LOCK.j
     A boolean set if the above has a lock (e.g. if another
     appicon is dropped over an appicon the lock will be 0)
               }
   where j = 0,...,m m = .i.DROPNUM-1


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    appIconID - an app icon ID
    handle    - where to write result


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    numMsg - the number of the messages


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAddAppIcon" LINK "WBAddAppIcon"} @{"WBAppIconSignal" LINK "WBAppIconSignal"} @{"WBFreeAppIcon" LINK "WBFreeAppIcon"}

@EndNode

@Node "help" "RxWB Functions - help"

  @{b}help@{ub} - returns a RxWB functions help string.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    string = help(funName)
    <funName/S>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Returns the arguments types mask of the function @{i}funName@{ui}.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    funName - a RxWB function name


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    string - a help string

@EndNode

@Node "WBAskToolType" "RxWB Functions - WBAskToolType"

  @{b}WBAskToolType@{ub} - reads an icon tooltype


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBAskToolType(icon,name,flags)
    <icon>,<name>,[flags]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Reads and returns the tooltype @{i}name@{ui} of the icon
    @{i}icon@{ui} .

    @{i}flags@{ui} may be KEY in which case, the function
    doesn't return the value of the tooltype, but just an
    ARexx boolean to indicate if the tooltype is present.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    icon  - an icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui}
    name  - the name of the tooltype to read
    flags - flags to controll the operation


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - the value of the tooltype:
          . an empty string           - the tooltype was not found and
                                        KEY was not specified in @{i}flags@{ui}
          . 0                         - the tooltype was not found and KEY was
                                        specified in @{i}flags@{ui}
          . 1                         - the tooltype was found and KEY was
                                        specified in @{i}flags@{ui}
          . the value of the tooltype - the tooltype was found and KEY
                                        was not specified in @{i}flags@{ui}


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBGetToolType" LINK "WBGetToolType"} @{"WBPutToolType" LINK "WBPutToolType"}
    @{"WBReadToolTypes" LINK "WBReadToolTypes"} @{"WBWriteToolTypes" LINK "WBWriteToolTypes"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBGettoolType" "RxWB Functions - WBGettoolType"

  @{b}WBGetToolType@{ub} - reads an icon tooltype


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBGetToolType(icon,name,var,default)
    <icon>,<name>,<var/S>,[default]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Reads the tooltype @{i}name@{ui} of the icon @{i}icon@{ui},
    writing its value in @{i}var@{ui} and using @{i}default@{ui},
    if @{i}name@{ui} can't be found.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    icon    - an icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui}
    name    - the name of the tooltype to read
    var     - where to write the tooltype value
    default - write this one in var if tooltype was not found


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - a boolean to indicate if the icon and tooltype were found


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAskToolType" LINK "WBAskToolType"} @{"WBPutToolType" LINK "WBPutToolType"}
    @{"WBReadToolTypes" LINK "WBReadToolTypes"} @{"WBWriteToolTypes" LINK "WBWriteToolTypes"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBPutToolType" "RxWB Functions - WBPutToolType"

  @{b}WBPutToolType@{ub} - writes an icon tooltype


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBPutToolType(icon,name,value,type,tool)
    <icon>,<name>,<value>,[type],[tool]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Sets the tooltype @{i}name@{ui} of the icon @{i}icon@{ui} to
    @{i}value@{ui}.

    If @{i}icon@{ui} can't be found and @{i}type@{ui} is supplied,
    a new brand icon of type @{i}type@{ui} is created, and if
    @{i}tool@{ui} is supplied, its default tool is set to @{i}tool@{ui} .

    @{i}icon@{ui} is an icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui} .

    @{i}type@{ui} is one of:
    - WBDISK
    - WBDRAWER
    - WBTOOL
    - WBPROJECT
    - WBGARBAGE
    - WBDEVICE
    - WBKICK
    - WBAPPICON


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    icon  - icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui}
    name  - the tooltype to write
    value - the value to set the tooltype to
    type  - create an icon of this type, if icon was not found
    tool  - set the default tool to this tool in the brand new icon


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAskToolType" LINK "WBAskToolType"} @{"WBGetToolType" LINK "WBGetToolType"}
    @{"WBReadToolTypes" LINK "WBReadToolTypes"} @{"WBWriteToolTypes" LINK "WBWriteToolTypes"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBReadToolTypes" "RxWB Functions - WBReadToolTypes"

  @{b}WBReadToolTypes@{ub} - reads all tooltypes of an icon


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBReadToolTypes(icon,stem)
    <icon>,<stem/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Reads all the tooltypes of the icon @{i}name@{ui}, setting
    in @{i}stem@{ui} the fields:

    - NUM
      The number of the tooltypes found

    - i
      The name of the i-th tooltype (i=0,,,NUM-1)

    - i.VALUE
      The value of the i-th tooltype (i=0,,,NUM-1)
      Note that a tooltype may not have a value, because
      of it is a key tool type or because of just no value
      is set. If so, this field is ""

    - i.KEY
      A boolean that indicates if the i-th tooltype (i=0,,,NUM-1)
      is a key one. A key tooltype is a tooltype with no "=" after
      its name. If i.KEY is 1, i.VALUE is ""

    - i.ACTIVE
      A boolean that indicates if the i-th tooltype (i=0,,,NUM-1)
      is active. A tooltype is considered not active if it is in
      round parenthesys

  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    icon - icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui}
    stem - where to write the tooltypes


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean. Note that if 0, IoErr() may be used
          to get the cause.

  @{b}Example@{ub}
    Reads all the tooltypes of an icon:

    if ~ReadToolTypes(icon,"tt") then do
        call PrintFault()
        exit
    end
    do i=0 to tt.num-1
      say "Name:["tt.i"]" "Value:["tt.i.Value"]" "Key:"tt.i.Key "Active:"tt.i.Active
    end

  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAskToolType" LINK "WBAskToolType"} @{"WBGetToolType" LINK "WBGetToolType"}
    @{"WBWriteToolTypes" LINK "WBWriteToolTypes"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBWriteToolTypes" "RxWB Functions - WBWriteToolTypes"

  @{b}WBWriteToolTypes@{ub} - sets all the tooltypes of an icon


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBWriteToolTypes(icon,stem,type,tool)
    <icon>,<stem/V>,[type],[tool]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Sets all the tooltypes of the icon @{i}icon@{ui}, reading from
    @{i}stem@{ui}.

    If @{i}icon@{ui} can't be found and @{i}type@{ui} is supplied,
    a new brand icon of type @{i}type@{ui} is created, and if
    @{i}tool@{ui} is supplied, its default tool is set to @{i}tool@{ui} .

    @{i}icon@{ui} is an icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui} .

    @{i}type@{ui} is one of:
    - WBDISK
    - WBDRAWER
    - WBTOOL
    - WBPROJECT
    - WBGARBAGE
    - WBDEVICE
    - WBKICK
    - WBAPPICON

    The fields read from @{i}stem@{ui} are:

    - i
      The name of the i-th tooltype

    - i.VALUE
      The value of the i-th tooltype. Note that if this
      is a key tooltype, this field is not considered.

    - i.KEY
      A boolean that indicates if the i-th tooltype is a
      key one. A key tooltype is a tooltype with no "=" after
      its name. If i.KEY is 1, i.VALUE is not considered.

    - i.ACTIVE
      A boolean that indicates if the i-th tooltype is
      active. If so this tooltype will be put in round
      parenthesys.

    - i.SKIP
      A boolean that indicates if the i-th tooltype
      has to be skipped.

    Note that the reading is made till @{i}stem@{ui}.i exists.


  @{b}Inputs@{ub}
    icon  - icon name without the @{i}.info@{ui}
    stem  - an ARexx stem to read values from
    type  - create an icon of this type, if icon was not found
    tool  - set the default tool to this tool in the brand new icon


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean. Note that if 0, IoErr() may be used
          to get the cause.


  @{b}Example@{ub}
    Add a couple of tooltypes to an icon:

    if ~ReadToolTypes(icon,"tt") then do
        call PrintFault()
        exit
    end

    i=tt.num
    tt.i="New1"
    tt.i.Value="NewValue1"

    i=i+1

    tt.i="New2"
    tt.i.Value="NewValue2"

    if ~WriteToolTypes(icon,"tt") then do
        call PrintFault()
        exit
    end

    Remove all the tooltypes wich start with "VIDEO":

    if ~ReadToolTypes(icon,"tt") then do
        call PrintFault()
        exit
    end

    do i=0 to tt.num-1
      if left(upper(tt.i),5)=="VIDEO" then tt.i.skip=1
    end

    if ~WriteToolTypes(icon,"tt") then do
        call PrintFault()
        exit
    end


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBAskToolType" LINK "WBAskToolType"} @{"WBGetToolType" LINK "WBGetToolType"}
    @{"WBReadToolTypes" LINK "WBReadToolTypes"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBChangeSelection" "RxWB Functions - WBChangeSelection"

  @{b}WBChangeSelection@{ub} - changes icon selection state.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBChangeSelection(obj,state,pattern,DTPattern)
    <obj>,[state],[pattern],[DTPattern]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Changes the selection state of the icons in the drawer
    @{i}object@{ui}, that may be not supplied or '', in which
    case the Workbench window is used.

    @{i}state@{ui} may be one of:
    - SELECT
      select the icons that match the contidions (default)

    - UNSELECT
      unselect the icons that match the contidions

    - TOGGLE
      toggle the selection state of the icons
      that match the contidions

    - KEEP
      normally, if an icon doesn't match the conditions
      it is unselected; setting this flag, the selection
      state of icons that don't match the conditions is
      not changed

    Just one of SELECT, UNSELECT and TOGGLE may be passed.

    @{i}pattern@{ui} is an AmigaDOS pattern: only the icons
    that match it will be considered (default: "#?").

    @{i}DTPattern@{ui} is an AmigaDOS pattern: only the icons
    which DataType base name matches it will be considered
    (default: "#?").


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    obj       - the name of an object or ''
    state     - the state to set
    pattern   - consider only icons matching it
    DTPattern - consider only icons wich base name matches it


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}Note@{ub}
    If workbench.library < V44 (AmigaOS 3.5) the function returns 0.

@EndNode

@Node "WBCloseObject" "RxWB Functions - WbCloseObject"

  @{b}WBCloseObject@{ub} - closes a Workbench object


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBCloseObject(obj)
    <obj>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Closes a Workbench object.


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    obj - the name of an object to close


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}Note@{ub}
    If workbench.library < V44 (AmigaOS 3.5) the function returns 0.

@EndNode

@Node "WBGetAttr" "RxWB Functions - WbGetAttr"

  @{b}WbGetAttr@{ub} - reads a Workbench attribute.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WbGetAttr(obj)
    <obj>,<attr>,<var/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Reads a Workbench object attribute.

    @{i}obj@{ui} may be '' in which case the back
    Workbench window is used.

    @{i}attr@{ui} is one of:
    - DefaultStackSize   /N
    - DrawerNotification /B
    - HiddenDeviceList   /V
    - ImageToFastRam     /B
    - IsOpen             /B
    - OpenDrawerList     /V
    - ProgramList        /V
    - SelectedIconList   /V
    - TitleBarEnabled    /B
    - TypeRestartTime    /N
    - VolumeGauge        /B

    If @{i}attr@{ui} is one of:
    - DefaultStackSize
    - DrawerNotification
    - ImageToFastRam
    - IsOpen
    - TitleBarEnabled
    - TypeRestartTime
    - VolumeGauge
    the value of the attribute is written in var.

    Example:
        call WBGetAttr('',"DRAWERNOTIFICATION","DN")
        say dn

    If @{i}attr@{ui} is one of:
    - HiddenDeviceList
    - OpenDrawerList
    - ProgramList
    - SelectedIconList
    the number of the entries are written in var.NUM and the
    entries in var.0, ..., var.N where N = var.NUM-1 .

    Example:
        call WBGetAttr('',"OPENDRAWERLIST","OD")
        say "OPENDRAWER:"od.num
        do i=0 to od.num-1
            say od.i
        end

  @{b}Input@{ub}
    obj  - the name of an object
    attr - the name of an attribute
    var  - an ARexx stem name


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}Note@{ub}
    If workbench.library < V44 (AmigaOS 3.5) the function returns 0.


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBSetAttr" LINK "WBSetAttr"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBOpenObject" "RxWB Functions - WBOpenObject"

  @{b}WBOpenObject@{ub} - opens a Workbench object.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBOpenObject(object,arg1,...)
    <obj>,{args}


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Opens a Workbench object.

    @{i}obj@{ui} may be the name of a drawer or the name of
    an application.

    Example:
        res = WBOpenObject('ram:')
        res = WBOpenObject('miami:miami')
        res = WBOpenObject('sys:utilities/multiview','s:startup-sequence')

  @{b}Input@{ub}
    obj  - the name of the object to open
    args - up to 14 arguments for obj

  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}Note@{ub}
    If workbench.library < V44 (AmigaOS 3.5) the function returns 0.

@EndNode

@Node "WBSetAttr" "RxWB Functions - WBSetAttrs"

  @{b}WBSetAttr@{ub} - sets a Workbench attribute.


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBSetAttr(obj,attr,value)
    <obj>,<attr>,<value>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Sets a Workbench attribute.

    @{i}obj@{ui} may be not supplied or '', in which case
    the Workbench window is used.

    @{i}attr@{ui} is one of:
    - AddHiddenDeviceName    /S
    - DefaultStackSize       /N
    - DrawerNotification     /B
    - ImageToFastRam         /B
    - RemoveHiddenDeviceName /S
    - TitleBarEnabled        /B
    - TypereStartTime        /N
    - VolumeGauge            /B


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    obj   - the name of an object
    attr  - the name of an attribute
    value - the value of the attribute


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean


  @{b}Note@{ub}
    If workbench.library < V44 (AmigaOS 3.5) the function returns 0.


  @{b}See@{ub}
    @{"WBGetAttr" LINK "WBGetAttr"}

@EndNode

@Node "WBInfo" "RxWB Functions - WBInfo"

  @{b}WBInfo@{ub} - open the icon information window


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBInfo(name,screen)
    <name>,[screen]


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Opens the icon information requester for the
    icon @{i}name@{ui}.


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    name   - an icon name without the ".icon" suffix
    screen - the name of a public screen where to open the requester on


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

@EndNode

@Node "WBGetIconAttrs" "RxWB Functions - WBGetIconAttrs"

  @{b}WBGetIconAttrs@{ub} - reads various attrs from an icon


  @{b}Synopsis@{ub}
    res = WBGetIconAttrs(icon,stem)
    <icon>,<stem/V>


  @{b}Function@{ub}
    Reads various @{i}icon@{ui} attributes writing their values in
    the following fields of @{i}stem@{ui}:

    - CurrentX
    - CurrentY
    - DefaultTool
    - StackSize
    - ToolWindow
    - Type


  @{b}Input@{ub}
    name - an icon name without the ".icon" suffix
    stem - a stem name filled with attrs values


  @{b}Result@{ub}
    res - an ARexx boolean

@EndNode


